47. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Herrich-Schaeffer" authorityYear="1846" box="[179,316,765,792]" class="Insecta" family="Thyrididae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="161" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Thyrididae</taxonomicName>
– window-winged moths
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="161" pageNumber="162" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="161.[140,1108,765,1038]" pageId="161" pageNumber="162">
Small to medium-sized (
<quantity box="[419,549,800,827]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7" metricValueMax="4.2" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="161" pageNumber="162" unit="mm" value="27.0" valueMax="42.0" valueMin="12.0">12–42 mm</quantity>
wingspan) moths with dark wings that have uneven margins and translucent spots. Larvae are borers or gall makers, or feed from within rolled or tied leaves.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="161.[140,1108,765,1038]" pageId="161" pageNumber="162">
Approximately 760 species of Th yrididae are known worldwide, primarily in tropical and subtropical areas. Ten species are known in North America; one of these has recently been collected in AB. No recent revisions exist for the group, but the AB species can be found in 
<bibRefCitation author="Covell CV Jr" box="[373,535,1011,1038]" pageId="161" pageNumber="162" refId="ref240257" refString="Covell CV Jr (1984) A field guide to moths of eastern North America. Houghton Mifflin, Boston, MA, Peterson Field Guide Series No. 30, 496 pp." type="book" year="1984">Covell (1984)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
